To get Quagga to work as if it were
installed by Ubuntu 14.04 LTE's apt-get mechanism:

1) Install packages texinfo and libreadline6-dev using apt-get

2) Install redis (version used: 1.0) system wide

2) Install hiredis (version used: ) system wide

3) Export $CFLAGS, $CPPFLAGS, and $LDFLAGS to reflect location of hiredis.h and its libhiredis.a.  I used: 

$CFLAGS="$CFLAGS -I/usr/local/include/hiredis
$CPPFLAGS="$CPPFLAGS -I/usr/local/include/hiredis"
$LDFLAGS="$LDFLAGS -L/usr/local/lib"

4)In quagga-0.99.24.1 subdirectory, type: Run autoconf and autoreconf --install

5)In quagga-0.99.24.1 subdirectory, type: 
  ./configure --sysconfdir=/etc/quagga --enable-vtysh --localstatedir=/var/run/quagga

6)Type: sudo make; sudo make install

7)Create group 'quaggavty' and add 'quagga' user to it.
    sudo useradd -m quagga
    sudo groupadd quaggavty
    sudo usermod -a -G quaggavty quagga

---- Everything below here may change depending on how David's MiniNeXT config works

8)Copy config/samples/{*.conf, daemons} to /etc/quagga.

9)Chown ownership of /etc/quagga and all files to quagga:quaggavty.

10)Copy config/samples/quagga to /etc/init.d.  Make sure it is owned by root and executable.
    sudo cp config/samples/quagga /etc/init.d. 
    sudo chown root /etc/init.d/quagga
    sudo chmod u+rwx /etc/init.d/quagga

11)Give user quagga permissions to modify /var/run.  
   mkdir -p /var/run/quagga
   chown quagga:quagga /var/run/quagga
   chmod 755 /var/run/quagga

12)Run ldconfig so that install picks up on new libraries.
   ldconfig
   ldconfig -p | grep libzebra

13)To see if things work: 
    bpgd &
    telnet localhost bgpd
    vtysh

Note, must be user 'quagga' to use vtysh.

